children.text: The fire-rated separating wall in this area has not been constructed in accordance with the BCA.
Part 3.7.3.2 Separating walls of the Building Code of Australia (BCA) requires that
‘A separating wall between Class 1 buildings, or a wall that separates a Class 1 building from a Class 10a building which is not associated with the Class 1 building must;
a.
have either;
i.
an FRL of not less than 60/60/60; or
ii.
be of masonry construction not less than 90 mm thick;
b.
commence at the footings or ground slab (see Figure 3.7.3.1), except for horizontal projections to which 3.7.3.5 applies (see Figure 3.7.3.4);
c.
extend;
i.
if the building has a non-combustible roof covering, to the underside of the roof covering (see Figure 3.7.3.1 and Figure 3.7.3.2); or
ii.
if the building has a combustible roof covering, to not less than 450 mm above the roof covering (see Figure 3.7.3.1);
d.
comply with (b) to (e) and 3.7.3.3 as applicable’
This separating wall must be immediately rectified so that it protects from the adjoining property from fire in accordance with the requirements of the BCA.
